{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"67cbaa4f-d690-4fcb-b948-328f3704e890","content":"This is a well-known MTP behavioral difference. **Exit code 8** means \"no tests were discovered.\" VSTest returned 0 in this case, but MTP treats it as an error by default.\n\n## The Fix\n\nSet the `TESTINGPLATFORM_EXITCODE_IGNORE` environment variable to tell MTP to map exit code 8 (no tests found) back to 0:\n\n**In your CI pipeline (recommended):**\n```yaml\nenv:\n  TESTINGPLATFORM_EXITCODE_IGNORE: 8\n```\n\n**Or per-command:**\n```bash\nTESTINGPLATFORM_EXITCODE_IGNORE=8 dotnet test\n```\n\nThis tells MTP: \"exit code 8 is not a failure.\" You can ignore multiple codes with a semicolon-delimited list (e.g., `8;2`).\n\n### Alternative: `--ignore-exit-code`\n\nIf you're calling the test executable directly (not via `dotnet test`), you can pass:\n```bash\n./TestProject --ignore-exit-code 8\n```\n\n### Why this happens\n\n| Runner | Zero tests discovered | Exit code |\n|--------|----------------------|-----------|\n| VSTest | Treated as success | **0** |\n| MTP | Treated as error | **8** |\n\nMTP is intentionally stricter — it flags empty test runs so misconfigurations don't silently pass. For your conditional-compilation scenario where zero tests is expected, the environment variable is the correct fix.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a34634a7-618d-4667-9242-549e91acb037","outputTokens":348,"requestId":"3402:15E90A:9CEE3F:B7472D:69F3FB78"},"id":"12631c97-ef2a-45fa-9bab-3edb16a5c986","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:01:53.548Z","parentId":"286e5606-3bc5-4830-88a3-56af62b8127e"}
